pting to establish the connection. Ignoring the `PCAP_SRC_IFREMOTE` type and treating it as a local interface could bypass security controls.", "code": "// Violation: Caller receives PCAP_SRC_IFREMOTE for 'type' but proceeds to use\n// pcap_open_live() as if it were a local interface, bypassing remote capture security.\nchar errbuf[PCAP_ERRBUF_SIZE];\nchar name[PCAP_BUF_SIZE];\nint type;\nunsigned char uses_ssl;\nconst char *source_string = \"rpcap://remote.example.com/capture\";\n// Parse the source string\nif (pcap_parsesrcstr_ex(source_string, &type, NULL, NULL, NULL, name, &uses_ssl, errbuf) == 0) {\n// Caller incorrectly assumes 'type' is PCAP_SRC_IFLOCAL despite it being PCAP_SRC_IFREMOTE\nif (type == PCAP_SRC_IFREMOTE) {\n// This is the violation: attempting to open a remote capture as a local device.\n// The correct action would be to use rpcap-specific functions or handle\n// remote capture security.\n// pcap_t *handle = pcap_open_live(name, 65535, 1, 0, errbuf); // Incorrect use for remote\n// This code snippet demonstrates the *intent* of the violation.\n// In a real scenario, the 'name' might be a device name on the remote host.\n// The violation is in the *choice* of pcap_open_live and the lack of\n// remote capture handling.\n// For demonstration, we'll simulate the incorrect path.\nprintf(\"Simulating incorrect handling of PCAP_SRC_IFREMOTE as local.\\n\");\n} else if (type == PCAP_SRC_IFLOCAL) {\n// Correct handling for local interface\n// pcap_t *handle = pcap_open_live(name, 65535, 1, 0, errbuf);\n} else if (type == PCAP_SRC_FILE) {\n// Correct handling for file\n// pcap_t *handle = pcap_open_offline(name, errbuf);\n}\n}"}, {"rule": "Parameter 3: **Rule: Ensure `userinfo` buffer is sufficiently sized to prevent buffer overflows when copying remote user information.**", "code": "#include <pcap.h>\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n#include <string.h>\n// Assume PCAP_BUF_SIZE is defined elsewhere, e.g., in pcap.h\n#ifndef PCAP_BUF_SIZE\n#defin